[normal]Q18 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Chairman[bold]:[bold] Yes, I think we understand that very well.  All the questions are open to you all but, as before, if you simply agree with whoever has answered the question first, it is not necessary for you to feel that you have to repeat the same points.  If you are particularly strongly in favour, if you nod, I will make sure that 
[normal]is recorded in the transcript.
[normal]Can we begin with a very general question?  As is very clear from all the evidence that we have and our first session, there is a very wide range of businesses and firms structured as partnerships, with a significant impact on the economy and certainly with very different sizes.  Is it right that the whole range of partnerships should be taxed in essentially the same way?  
[normal]Malcolm Gammie:[bold] One starting point is to say that a partnership is merely one of the various forms in which business and other activities can be carried on and, ideally, you would want to tax all those different structures in a way that ensured that people who were earning similar amounts in respect of their activities were paying similar amounts of tax.  Of course, we very rarely achieve that particular objective as part of our tax system, but unless there is some objective difference between the way in which partnerships are structured and are being used in a particular way, you would probably try to tax them similarly.  
[normal]Chris Sanger:[bold] If I can add to that, the same question could be applied to companies more generally.  We have a single system of taxation that applies to all companies, and if you take the nuance of the partnership, given 
[normal]that 
[normal]the partnership is
[normal] 
[normal]tax transparent, if you were to take a different approach to the members or partners of that partnership, you 
[normal]would 
[normal]do it at the partner or member level rather than at the partnership level itself.
[normal]Professor Freedman:[bold] I would agree on the neutrality point.  I would just add that every time a new kind of tax creature is created you create new opportunities, so the idea of having special rules for certain partnerships may seem superficially attractive but will create problems because there will then be arbitr
[normal]age and avoidance around that.
[normal]Q19 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Chairman[bold]:[bold] I know, Professor Freedman, 
[normal]that 
[normal]you have a special interest in small and medium
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]sized businesses and, again from the evidence we have been hearing so far, there is a particularly wide range.  On one side, there are the very large professional partnerships and, on the other side, the husband and wife or two
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]person small business.  Do you think that taxing the very small partnerships in the same way is the best approach? 
[normal]Professor Freedman:[bold] Ideally, some of the largest partnerships should be corporations and should be taxed as corporations.  However, I do agree with Malcolm
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Gammie that the ideal should be to reduce the differences as much as possible between the different types of taxation, rather than creating new differences.  One can say that the husband
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]and
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]wife business looks very, very different from the 500
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]partnership, but there is a spectrum and you have to decide where you draw the line across that spectrum
